column43:
A scrappy expanse of silky refuges and capture webs littered with body parts of previous victims. When preferred prey is entangled, the female spiders emerge from their 'nests' and overpower it by grabbing its extremities. In this case, a wasp https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/9319446. 
Presumably they inject venom because after a minute or so the prey stops struggling. Then they snip it out of the web and carry it into one of several 'nests' or refuges.
 Unwanted prey, often beetles (see https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/9319435 ) are also killed but sometimes left in the web, uneaten.  Ants, in this case, Maranoplus ( https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/9319390 )scavenge around the periphery of the webs, feasting on unwanted beetles or other left-overs.

column43:
7 part photostory, this one is for the spider which can be seen in 2nd and succeeding photos.
Photo 1: 
I Thought It Was A Yellowjacket 
When I came inside my house, what I thought was a yellow jacket came in with me. This is a problem because I like to go barefoot and I have cats that could get stung also. I went to get a broom to try to slap it down out of the air. When I came back it had gone to a window with blinds. I discovered that a tiny spider had solved my problem. The "yellow jacket" had been caught in a web. Later when I got the insect identified by experts, it turned out to be a fly pretending to be a yellow jacket. This is an example of Batesian mimicry which is when a harmless, tasty species mimics another species that is toxic or foul tasting or dangerous in order to be protected from predators. Sure fooled me. It did not deter the spider. 
Photo 2: 
Spider To The Rescue 
The spider solved my problem. Here is the spider coming to take a look at what it caught in its web. I was shooting these photos through open blinds. 
Photo 3: 
Underside Of The Spider 
I took this shot to help with getting an id on the spider. 
Photo 4: 
Topside Of The Spider 
As the spider wrapped some silk around the fly's legs, I got a shot of the top side of the spider. 
Photo 5: 
Uncropped Shot For Perspective 
I left this shot uncropped to show how I was having to do this, shooting between two blinds slats. 
Photo 6: 
Spider Injects venom 
The spider may have been fooled by the mimicry because it avoided the end of the fly where a stinger would be if it were a wasp. What the spider did, as shown here, was to bite the leg which injected venom. The fly stopped struggling shortly after that. 
Photo 7: 
The Spider Won 
I had to leave at this point so took this last photo of the spider. Several hours later when I got back the fly was wrapped up in silk for a later meal. The next morning there was nothing left to be seen.

column43:
This hawk was feeding on a ground squirrel in the shadows. I walked right by and would have missed it if it hadn't jumped out behind me.  When I heard the noise and turned around it was maybe 10 feet from me, but I guess didn't want to give up the rest of its meal. I took a step or two back and it walked over and continued feeding. Note the bit of squirrel meat visible in its bill in photo 4.

I returned about 90 min. later and took some pictures of the remains of the prey animal listed here: 
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/55656285

column43:
Frank's uh ... Brown Sparrowhawk strikes again

Photos kind courtesy of Frank Curtis. Took an hour and 20 minutes for the snake to subdue and swallow the Sparrow. Successfully this time. Fascinating that a relatively large snake survives in a heavily built-up area in the middle of cat- and traffic-infested town. Also, that a fundamentally nocturnal rodent-hunter has adapted to lie in wait for birds at the base of the garden feeder, by day ... column43:
With Valeri Ponzo. We left at 1445, when the weather was sunny and 92 degrees ("feels like" 105), with calm winds.

Swallowing a Cuban Treefrog. Val heard the frog squeal, then we watched it puff up to avoid being swallowed. Eventually, the snake deflated it, and it went down much faster.

A very slimy and gooey mess.
column72:
With Valeri Ponzo. We left at 1445, when the weather was sunny and 92 degrees ("feels like" 105), with calm winds.

Val heard the frog squeal, then we saw it in the jaws of a Black Racer. It took maybe 10 minutes for the snake to completely swallow the frog, which puffed up. Once the snake "popped" the frog -- no, we did not hear a "pop" -- then it went down much faster. Still, a very sloppy, slimy mess.

Ähnlichste gemeinsam mit Messor barbarus auftretende Art ist Messor capitatus, mit der sie in eine gemeinsame Artengruppe gestellt wird. Die Arten sind am besten an großen Arbeiterinnen (Majores) unterscheidbar. Bei diesen ist das Propodeum bei Messor barbarus oben abgerundet, bei Messor capitatus eckig. Außerdem ist der Kopf dieser Arbeiterinnen bei Messor barbarus deutlich rötlich gefärbt, während Messor capitatus einfarbig schwarz ist.[1][2]

https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/118487-Messor-barbarus?locale=de-DE

column72: I’d been watching my woods because of the dead opossum [ https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/150086636 ] I’d moved there.  Nothing amiss when walking out there 3/6/2023.  Morning of 3/7, from my window I saw red among the brown leaves.  With binos, I saw a big streak of bright red blood and a rib cage, then a coyote carrying something out of my sight.  The red blood had completely faded away within a half hour, which indicated to me the kill had been relatively recent.  Morning of 3/8, I ventured out and found where a young deer had been taken apart all over the place and (presumably) other creatures had been picking it clean.  My guess is that coyote(s) had pounced on the deer where it had bedded down for the night.  The dead opossum was untouched.

There was an owlet in the box the night before, never thought a snake could climb a tree like this. Thinking this might be a southern Timber Rattler, not sure what else would tangle with a big owl. It appears the snake got the owlet, then laid a trap or somehow tangled with one of the adults. Later photos showed what looked like an owl wing hanging from the box, with just one parent bird seen on a nearby branch. Then the wing was gone. Nothing at the box after May 22. Trying to id the snake if possible and complete a story here with just a few snapshots from the game camera.

column43: Flower scarab - Valgus canaliculatus (males, ~5 mm) These were all over the persimmon flowers, often disappearing most of the way down into the flower. I have usually found them on Viburnum previously. These always remind me of ticks. Genus name is Latin valgus, "bow-legged". These are canaliculatus (versus V. seticollis), based on: - dark reddish brown (vs. piceous) - anterior tibiae with 3 slender, widely-separated teeth on outer side (vs. 5-6) - pronotum with many small teeth along edge (vs. large teeth) - overlapping cream-colored scales on abdominal sternites (vs. non-overlapping, tawny); visible in one image Female of canaliculatus has long process on pygidium, lacking here, so these should be males. It seems that primarily males visit flowers (Ratclifee and Paulsen). The species is termetophilous--eggs, larvae, and adults can be found in the galleries of Reticulitermes flavipes (several references below). References - BugGuide bugguide.net/node/view/5242 - Dillon and Dillon, A Manual of Common Beetles of Eastern North America (Row, Peterson, and Company, 1961), p. 558, plate 53(16) - Evans, Beetles of Eastern North America (Princeton University Press, 2014), p. 177 - Harpootlian, Scarab Beetles of South Carolina (Clemson University, 2001), p. 124, figs. 243, 285 - Ratcliffe and Jameson, Generic Guide to New World Scarabs unsm-ento.unl.edu/Guide/Scarabaeoidea/Scarabaeidae/Cetoni... - Ratcliffe and Paulsen, The Scarabaeoid Beetles of Nebraska (Bulletin of the University of Nebraska State Museum, Vol 22, 2008), pp. 503-4, fig. 688

column72:
This is the nicest looking wild pawpaw on the property. Seems to be a good combo of enough leaf litter (large oaks and magnolias nearby) and not too much shade. There is one larger than this at the edge of the forested area. It has the best soil but also the least light. It never seems to have any fruit. There are several other smaller ones in sunnier sandier areas. I have never gotten to try the fruit since animals always get them first. They are great for attracting Zebra Swallowtails though. Caterpillar on this bush: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/221016473

It's too expensive to water the garden enough for most vegetables with such sandy soil. Hence the container gardening. So this pawpaw is not getting any special treatment. It looked terrible during the severe drought last year (some wild bushes and trees died), but it bounced right back.

column43: A Great Blue Heron caught a large fish that it struggled to swallow. A Pacific Staghorn Sculpin?
column72: Two Great Blue Herons were fishing where water from the lagoon gushes through a culvert into the harbor. One caught this very large fish with brown/green back, white belly, and banded pectoral fins. The heron struggled to grab it well enough to swallow it, and dropped it a few times, always recovering it, and finally swallowing it whole. Then, of course, continuing to hunt for more! Maybe a Pacific Staghorn Sculpin?

column7: Ridge Trail, New Orleans, LA, US

column72:
This is the nicest looking wild pawpaw on the property. Seems to be a good combo of enough leaf litter (large oaks and magnolias nearby) and not too much shade. There is one larger than this at the edge of the forested area. It has the best soil but also the least light. It never seems to have any fruit. There are several other smaller ones in sunnier sandier areas. I have never gotten to try the fruit since animals always get them first. They are great for attracting Zebra Swallowtails though. Caterpillar on this bush: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/221016473

It's too expensive to water the garden enough for most vegetables with such sandy soil. Hence the container gardening. So this pawpaw is not getting any special treatment. It looked terrible during the severe drought last year (some wild bushes and trees died), but it bounced right back.
Observation is for the plant.

column7: Florida, Hernando, Chassahowitzka Wildlife and Environmental Area, Retriever Road
column43:
With Don Fraser; a visit to see what was around. The weather at 0943 was sunny and 68 degrees ("feels like" 66), with a light breeze, We made three stops. Alice Herden told me about the first stop; a recent burn with thousands of Liatris stalks. Unfortuntely, we did not see many native arthropods (but Western Honeybees were common). I don't think I had ever seen so many treefroggies (including many Pinewoods Treefrogs)!

These are my cell-phone images, which are GPS-enabled. In some cases, I am uploading a cell-phone image just to have the precise location, and I will later upload my (superior) camera images.

column43:
I usually don't take many photos of dead things that I find, hoping to find live ones eventually, but I came across 4 or 5 of these earlier on the hike and was beginning to wonder why.
Most were sitting across rocks, all posed as if they had just died on the spot while walking along.

Apparently a fungus that emerges between the segments of a millipede usually 12 to 24 hours after rain.

Observation duplicated for the millipede here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/256022698

column43:
A gull that was trying to eat a fish that might have been a bit too big to swallow. After watching it fail and drop it several times, I walked over to see what it was and took some pictures.
Listed here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/260195677

I don't know if the gull caught the fish or just found it. The gull walked back to continue trying after I retreated, and half an hour later the fish was gone. There had been some other gulls around, showing interest as well, so I don't know if it was swallowed whole, torn apart, or just carried off.

column7: Florida, Hernando, Chassahowitzka Wildlife and Environmental Area
column43: With Don Fraser, Clint Gibson, Shelley Rutkin, and Liz Childress; a successful chase of two rare bees. We found _Colletes banksi_ pollening on Dahoon Holly (_Ilex cassine_) -- a new food plant -- and we found several _Melissodes mitchelli_, the star of the show. According to Clint (who knows these things), mitchelli had not been identifiable photographed in the wild previously! It all started on 12 April 2025, when Don, Clint, and I participated in the Annuteliga Hammock butterfly count. During the count, I saw a bee gathering pollen from a prickly pear cactus. I took one cell-phone photograph then the bee was gone. Later, I showed Clint the photo, and he said that could be a real good bee, _Melissodes mitchelli_, which is a Florida endemic, is exclusive to prickly pear pollen ("oligolectic"), and is known from just a few records, all of them specimens. It turns out that Don had photographed probably the same bee last year at Chassahowitzka Wildlife and Environmental Area on a trip with me and Alice Herden. Then, Cliff and his wife found and collected a male _Melissodes mitchelli_ (Clint has permits ...) at Starkey Wilderness Preserve on 17 April 2025. So the stage was set for this day at Chassahowitzka. Clint found and captured (but did not collect) a _Melissodes mitchelli_, which we all photographed before Clint released it. We started out on Rattlesnake Camp Road and then drove Scrub Island Road. Finally, we drove 3 Bridge Road to the sandhills area at the northern edge of the property. I took my first photographs at 1055 and my last at 1539. The weather at the start was sunny, 84 degrees ("feels like" 85), and with SW winds at 9 MPH.

column43:
A solo visit the day after Valeri Ponzo, Don Fraser, and I visited. Valeri noticed a small tiny grub on a fruit of a Litttleleaf Sensitive Briar (_Mimosa microphylla_) when she examined her photographs after arriving home. I went back today to get more photographs of the grub. And while I was there, I added 35 other new records, to put me over the 5,000-records mark for the iNaturalist project for Chassahowitzka. My first photograph was taken at 1049 and my last at 1133. I took no camera photographs. I forgot to record the weather, but it was sunny and close to 90 degrees ("feels like" temperature probably mid-90s), with a light breeze.

Two Netted Pawpaws were really hit hard by Pawpaw Webworm Moths.

column43:
A solo visit. I started late (1150) because I could not motivate myself to get out of bed. The weather at my arrival was sunny and 91 degrees ("feels like" 100), with a light breeze. I surveyed Scrub Island Road for the first time this year, and I found an old logging tram that headed west from the end of the road. I followed the tram until it ended; it was a nice shady walk, and provided me with my first Appalachian Brown of Chassahowitzka. (The tram also furnished my first EVER photograph of a Barred Owl in Hernando County!!! Talk about being long overdue)! There were also many Needle Palms along the tram. I stopped at the Dukes' Skippper spot along 3 Bridge Road (finding little) before I headed to my final spot near the start of North Road. I once again encountered an agitated female "Southestern" American Kestrel, so there must be a nest in the kestrel box. I left at 1501, when the weather was sunny, 94 degrees ("feels like" 104), and breezy.

These are my cell-phone photographs (161 records), all time-stamped and geolocated.

column7: Florida, Hernando, Perry Oldenburg Wildlife and Environmental Area
column43:
A solo visit after four days of frequent all-day rain; I simply had to get out somewhere, 
and I had not visited Perry Oldenburg in at least two months. I walked a unique path today: the west fenceline to the south fenceline, then northeast under the powerline to the east-west trail that continues east from Yes Dear Lane, then south along the east fenceline, cross country (through recent burns) to the nature trail, clockwise, under the powerline to continue along the southern nature trail to the lake, then along its eastern side to the northern nature trail back to Little Red. The weather at the start (1112) was overcast, 88 degrees ("feels like" 100, with probably 95% humidity), with a light breeze. The weather was the same when I left at 1421. Several observations: (1) There were 20 or more cocoons on the western barbed-wire fenceline; iNat's AI identified them as Southern Flannel Moths (Megalopyge opercularis), which makes sense. (2) Several dozen butterflies (swallowtails including many Zebra Swallowtails, Zebra Longwing, Gulf Fritillary, Southern Dogface, and duskywings) were nectaring abundantly on Florida Pusley (Richardia scabra) at the very southwestern corner of the preserve; I was not aware it was such a butterfly plant. (3) It was a great mushroom/fungus day, with hundreds of individuals of many species (too bad most will never be RGed). (4) Clusterspike False Indigo (Amorpha herbacea) is just starting to bloom. (5) Manyflower Beardtongue (Penstemon multiflorus) is blooming abundantly under the powerline. (6) The trail along the powerline is growing up with grasses and forbs; I found no tiger beetles here (although I found two elsewhere). (7) Florida False Sunflower (Phoebanthus grandiflorus) was blooming over much of the preserve, especially along the southern nature trail west of the powerline. (8) About every third Florida False Sunflower bloom had an Orange Blister Beetle (Nemognatha piazata) on it. (9) Sand Post Oak (Quercus margaretiae) has very attractive leaves when young; I photographed several in a recently-burned area. (10) The lake is finally receding after being formed in October 2024 following the passage of one or two hurricanes. Dozens of flooded Slash Pine skeletons dot the former boundary. (11) I probably got some lifer plants; I can't think of any insect that might be a lifer, and I saw very few spiders or vertebrates (although three Green Anoles was nice).

These are my cell-phone photographs (representing 226 records), all time-stamped and geolocated.

column43:
This bald eagle slipped in right after the other and thus avoided most of the gull swarm, since they were still regrouping after the first, just a moment earlier. Both took murres. Since the two flew off together to the same area, it seems likely they're mates.

Twelve minutes later, an eagle flew in again, and got another murre. After staring at the photos for a long time, I believe it was this eagle, again, due to the pattern of feather breakage in the wings. It didn't get to avoid the gulls this time, and took another murre, as seen in the fifth photo.

Prey: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/296198155

Other eagle, possible mate: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/296198161

column43:
With Don Fraser. The weather at the start was sunny and 76 degrees ("feels like" 76), with a light breeze. I counted the following butterflies, mostly on the blooming Bristle Thistles: 68 swallowtails, 69 skippers, 7 sulphurs, and 1 Gulf Fritillary. This was the day that I learned that Larger Florida Mantises are killing machines, something I had wondered about in 2023, as the numbers of skippers declined through the fall season. Don and I watched one mantis capture and consume one Twin-spot Skipper (1024-1035) and then immediately capture and eat a second Twin-spot Skipper (1037-1041), then capture and consume a third Twin-spot Skipper (1055-1108), and then instantly start hunting a Palmetto Skipper, which escaped at the last possible milli-second, and then try to capture a Palamedes Swallowtail, which also escaped at the last milli-second. I did not enjoy watching the killing sequences, but I did not intervene at all. We left here at 1122 (after 2 hours!) and headed to Scrub Island Road.

I NEED TO ADD MY REMAINING CAMERA PHOTOGRAPHS AND THEN COMBINE PHONE + CAMERA PHOTOS REPRESENTING THE SAME RECORD.

column7: Florida, Hernando, Chassahowitzka Wildlife and Environmental Area
column43:
With Valeri Ponzo, who wanted to see bugs but was not available tomorrow or next weekend. I suggested she come up today even though I had to work from noon afterward. (I had not checked the weather for today, which turned out be stormy, 1040-1140). I iNatted the parking area for 15 minutes until Val arrived, then we took my car to east of the thistle pond on Rattlesnake Camp Road. This is where Liz Childress photographed a Juniper Hairstreak this past Monday, and where I spent 80 minutes here yesterday, looking unsuccessfully for it. Val and I spent 90 minutes here before a storm front came through, and I had to leave for work. (Afterward, Val spent much time in the Indigo Lane sandhills, finally leaving Chassahowitzka at 1715!). In some cases, I am submitting records for the same individuals that I photographed here yesterday, which I am presuming is acceptable since they were photographed on different days. Yesterday, I found two Bleeding Flower Moths here; today, we found FIVE in a plot maybe the size of a suburban yard. It was incredible! Val also found a plant that might be a lifer for me. I wished I could have spent all day out here -- Val found several other flower moths along Indigo Lane -- but this is the single Saturday where every three months, I have the same two jobs. Oh well!

I am submitting 102 records. I have placed my camera photographs pretty accurately.

column43:
Western Lynx Spider (Oxyopes scalaris) eating a wasp (Suborder Apocrita) by the coast at Landels-Hill Big Creek Reserve in Big Sur, CA. Last photo shows the Big Creek Bridge and coastal scrub habitat.

BugGuide: https://bugguide.net/index.php?q=search&keys=Oxyopes%20scalaris

Link to prey: a wasp (Suborder Apocrita): https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/325834703

Western Lynx Spider (Oxyopes scalaris) is an arachnid in the Grass Lynx Spiders (Oxyopes) genus and the the Wolf Spiders and Allies (Lycosoidea) superfamily. Like other Lynx Spiders, 
Grass Lynx Spiders are easily recognizable by the 6 larger eyes arranged hexagonally on top of the head (prosoma), with the remaining smaller 2 eyes in front. They are also characterized by long spine-like bristles (setae) on their legs. They are ambush predators, actively hunting prey by sight. 

xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx

SPIDERS are Arachnids (Class Arachnida). Arachnids are NOT insects--they are joint-legged invertebrate animals in the Arthropods (Arthropoda) phylum that have 8 legs and 2 body segments, the cephalothorax and the abdomen. Arachnids (Arachnida Class) includes, among others, spiders, scorpions, ticks, MITES, pseudoscorpions, harvestmen, camel spiders, whip spiders and vinegaroons.
Spiders, mites, and ticks have their body divided into 2 sections, unlike the other commonly seen group of arthropods – the insects – who have their body divided into 3 sections.

Western Lynx Spider (Oxyopes scalaris) is an arachnid in the Grass Lynx Spiders (Oxyopes) genus and the the Wolf Spiders and Allies (Lycosoidea) superfamily. Like other Lynx Spiders, 
Grass Lynx Spiders are easily recognizable by the 6 larger eyes arranged hexagonally on top of the head (prosoma), with the remaining smaller 2 eyes in front. They are also characterized by long spine-like bristles (setae) on their legs. They are ambush predators, actively hunting prey by sight.

SPIDERS are Arachnids (Class Arachnida). Arachnids are NOT insects--they are joint-legged invertebrate animals in the Arthropods (Arthropoda) phylum that have 8 legs and 2 body segments, the cephalothorax and the abdomen. Arachnids (Arachnida Class) includes, among others, spiders, scorpions, ticks, MITES, pseudoscorpions, harvestmen, camel spiders, whip spiders and vinegaroons.
Spiders, mites, and ticks have their body divided into 2 sections, unlike the other commonly seen group of arthropods – the insects – who have their body divided into 3 sections.

The Amargosa River stretches about 185 miles (298 km), winding through southern Nevada into eastern California before vanishing into Death Valley’s Badwater Basin. It rises near Pahute Mesa in Nye County and drains a vast desert basin of roughly 14,000 square kilometers. For most of its course the river flows underground, hidden within aquifers, surfacing only in rare segments near Beatty, Nevada, and in California’s Amargosa Canyon near Tecopa. These brief above-ground stretches sustain pockets of dense vegetation and wildlife, contrasting sharply with the arid desert surroundings. The river’s intermittent surface flow is often triggered by storms, but its subterranean path is continuous, feeding ecosystems quietly beneath the desert floor. Its protected 26-mile scenic corridor between Shoshone and Dumont Dunes highlights both its ecological importance and its unusual character as a river that is at once extensive in reach yet elusive in visibility.

Amargosa River is "often called the "Crown Jewel of the Mojave Desert." The Amargosa River is the only free-flowing river in the Death Valley region of the Mojave Desert, providing a rare and lush riparian habitat in the desert" . . . Dancers (Argia genus): "is a diverse genus which contains about 114 species and many more to be described. It is also the largest genus in Argiinae. They are found in the Western Hemisphere. This genus of Damselflies are known as Dancers because of the distinctive jerky form of flight they use which contrasts with the straightforward direct flight of bluets, forktails and other pond damselflies. They are usually to be seen in the open where they catch flying insects on the wing rather than flying about among vegetation picking off sedentary prey items. They tend to land and perch flat on the ground, logs and rocks.[2] When perched, they usually hold their wing slightly raised above the abdomen. The males of most species are some combination of black and blue but they can easily be told from similarly coloured bluets by their mode of flight. Some species have red eyes and others a copper-coloured thorax. Many species have humeral stripes, either notched or forked at the end or narrowed in the centre. The wings have short petioles and are relatively broad close to the base. Unlike most of the Coenagrionidae, dancers are often associated with flowing water." https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/47977-Argia

Dancers (Argia): Dragonflies and Damselflies of the West by Dennis Paulson, 2009, p. 140-141, 156 (male appendage diagrams).

Dragonflies and Damselflies are flying insects in the Order Odonata. Adults are highly aerial. Larvae are aquatic and predatory. Adult dragonflies are characterized by a pair of large, multifaceted compound eyes, two pairs of strong, transparent wings, sometimes with colored patches, and an elongated body. Dragonflies can be mistaken for the closely related Damselflies, but the wings of most dragonflies are held flat, outward at a right angle, away from the body, while damselflies hold their wings folded at rest, above, or parallel to the abdomen. Dragonflies are agile fliers, while damselflies have a weaker, fluttery flight.
Odonata pairs oviposit in tandem. They are joined together while laying eggs on water. When joined together, they exhibit "mate-guarding" behavior while the female lays eggs with tail-dipping motions into water. They stay fairly low between descents and often tap the water repeatedly before moving a short distance and doing it again.

Dragonflies and Damselflies of the West by Dennis Paulson, 2009, (Includes Odonate Anatomy p. 22-26)
